<!-- PROBLEM -->
<section id="problem">
  <div class="container">
    <p class="section-label">The Problem</p>
    <h2 class="section-title">Cloud AI fails first where reliability matters most.</h2>
    <p class="section-body">The first market is in African operating environments, but the problem is broader: businesses cannot run core workflows on AI tools that depend on constant connectivity, easy cross-border data movement, and cloud-first pricing.</p>
    <div class="problem-grid">
      <div class="problem-card">
        <div class="problem-icon">📡</div>
        <div class="problem-title">Connectivity cannot be a requirement</div>
        <div class="problem-text">In the launch markets, internet shutdowns and poor connectivity make cloud AI unreliable at the exact moment teams need it. That same failure mode appears anywhere operations depend on unstable networks.</div>
      </div>
      <div class="problem-card">
        <div class="problem-icon">⚡</div>
        <div class="problem-title">Infrastructure assumptions break down</div>
        <div class="problem-text">Most AI products are designed for always-on cloud environments. Many businesses operate with tighter hardware budgets, unstable power, and real limits on what can stay connected all day.</div>
      </div>
      <div class="problem-card">
        <div class="problem-icon">🔒</div>
        <div class="problem-title">Data control is not optional</div>
        <div class="problem-text">Local hosting, internal control, and auditability are becoming baseline requirements. The launch region makes that pressure obvious, but the same demand exists across regulated and security-sensitive workflows everywhere.</div>
      </div>
    </div>
  </div>
</section>

<div class="divider"></div>

